{"id": "957", "instruction": "When $x = 1, -1, 2$, $f(x) = 0, -3, 4$. The quadratic interpolation polynomial for $f(x)$ is____.\n\nOptions:\nA. $$\nL_{2}( x)=\\frac{7} {8} \\, x^{2}+\\frac{2} {9} \\, x-\\frac{6} {7}\n$$\nB. $$\nL_{2}( x)=\\frac{5} {9} \\, x^{2}+\\frac{1} {2} \\, x-\\frac{4} {5}\n$$\nC. $$\nL_{2}( x)=\\frac{3} {2} \\, x^{2}+\\frac{5} {6} \\, x-\\frac{1} {4}\n$$\nD. $$\nL_{2}( x)=\\frac{4} {7} \\, x^{2}+\\frac{7} {9} \\, x-\\frac{1} {5}\n$$\nE. $$\nL_{2}( x)=\\frac{6} {11} \\, x^{2}+\\frac{4} {7} \\, x-\\frac{3} {8}\n$$\nF. $$\nL_{2}( x)=\\frac{1} {3} \\, x^{2}+\\frac{7} {10} \\, x-\\frac{5} {6}\n$$\nG. $$\nL_{2}( x)=\\frac{3} {4} \\, x^{2}+\\frac{4} {5} \\, x-\\frac{2} {3}\n$$\nH. $$\nL_{2}( x)=\\frac{2} {5} \\, x^{2}+\\frac{1} {3} \\, x-\\frac{3} {2}\n$$\nI. $$\nL_{2}( x)=\\frac{1} {2} \\, x^{2}+\\frac{2} {3} \\, x-\\frac{5} {4}\n$$\nJ. $$\nL_{2}( x)=\\frac{5} {6} \\, x^{2}+\\frac{3} {2} \\, x-\\frac{7} {3}\n$$", "output": "J"}
